{{Infobox person | name = Erinn Hayes | image =Erinn Hayes by Gage Skidmore.jpg | imagesize = 220px | caption = Hayes at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]. | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1976|5|25}} | birthname = Alexandra Erinn Carter | birth_place = [[San Francisco]], California, United States | alma_mater = [[University of Colorado Boulder]] |occupation = Actress, Comedian |yearsactive = 2001–present | website = | spouse = {{marriage|Jack Hayes|2004}} |children = 2 }} '''Alexandra Erinn Hayes''' (''[[née]]'' '''Carter'''; born May 25, 1976) is an American actress and comedian. She is known for her role as Dr. Lola Spratt on the [[Adult Swim]] sitcom ''[[Childrens Hospital (TV Series)|Childrens Hospital]]''. She has played roles in a number of network sitcoms, including Alison on ''[[The Winner (TV series)|The Winner]]'' (2007), Melanie Clayton on ''[[Worst Week]]'' (2008–2009), and Sheila on ''[[Guys with Kids]]'' (2012–2013). In 2012, she had her first feature film role in the black comedy ''[[It's a Disaster]]''. She also starred in the Amazon series ''[[The Dangerous Book for Boys (TV series)|The Dangerous Book for Boys]]'' and the first season of the CBS sitcom ''[[Kevin Can Wait]]''.
==Career== In 2005, Hayes appeared as a chef Becky Sharp on FOX's short-lived ''[[Kitchen Confidential (TV series)|Kitchen Confidential]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2005/12/09/fox-closes-kitchen-confidential-doubles-up-arrested-20052/7045/|title=FOX Closes 'Kitchen Confidential,' Doubles Up 'Arrested'|work=The Futon Critic|author=Brian Ford Sullivan|date=December 9, 2005|accessdate=June 3, 2017}}</ref> Also, in that same year, she played the role of [[Pam Dawber]] in the TV movie ''Behind the Camera: The Unauthorized Story of Mork & Mindy'' alongside costar [[Chris Diamantopoulos]]. Hayes played Alison on the television show ''[[The Winner (TV series)|The Winner]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title= 2007 Cancelled Shows: FOX Cancels Plenty of Series|url=http://www.tvseriesfinale.com/2007/05/2007_cancelled_shows_fox_cancels_plenty_of_series.php |accessdate=June 12, 2007 }}{{dead link|date=August 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>
Hayes played the role of Dr. Lola Spratt in the satirical comedy series ''[[Childrens Hospital]]'' on [[Adult Swim]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/spikefriedman/2016/06/17/childrens-hospitals-erinn-hayes-on-the-best-job-of-her-life-and-charting-a-career-in-comedy|title=Erinn Hayes From 'Childrens Hospital' On The Best Job Of Her Life And Charting A Career In Comedy|website=[[Forbes]]|first=Spike|last=Friedman|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=June 3, 2017}}</ref> She was nominated for an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Actress in a Short Form Comedy or Drama Series|Outstanding Actress in a Short Form Comedy or Drama Series]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/emmy-nominations-new-short-form-categories-rob-corddry-childrens-hospital-1201706483/|title= ‘Childrens Hospital’ Emmy Nominations: How Rob Corddry’s Web Experiment Turned Into an Awards Contender|website=[[Indiewire]]|first=Jude|last=Dry|date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=June 3, 2017}}</ref>
She played the role of Melanie Clayton on the [[CBS]] comedy series ''[[Worst Week]]''. The series was an Americanized version of the British comedy ''[[The Worst Week of My Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/erinn-hayes-previews-1002954/|title=Great Expectations Await Worst Week's Erinn Hayes|website=[[TV Guide]]|first=Joyce|last=Eng|date=February 15, 2009|accessdate=June 3, 2017}}</ref> She then later starred on the [[NBC]] comedy series ''[[Guys with Kids]]''. She starred in films such as ''[[It's a Disaster]]'', ''[[The Watch (2012 film)|The Watch]]'', and ''[[They Came Together]]''. Hayes co-starred in the second season of [[Hulu]]'s reality TV parody series ''The Hotwives of Las Vegas'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/169275_casey_wilson_the_hotwives_of_las_vegas_trailer/|title=The Hotwives Head to Las Vegas in the Exclusive Trailer for Season 2|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|first=Stacy|last=Lambe|date=August 4, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2017}}</ref>
In 2015, she performed as an inmate on the band [[Dengue Fever (band)|Dengue Fever]]'s video for the song "No Sudden Moves."
In 2016, Hayes began co-starring in the CBS series ''[[Kevin Can Wait]]'', portraying the role of Kevin Gable's wife Donna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/erinn-hayes-cast-lead-kevin-james-cbs-comedy-series-1201708553/|title=Erinn Hayes Set As the Female Lead In Kevin James’ CBS Comedy Series|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/cbs-fall-premiere-dates-2016-1201776569/|title=CBS Sets Fall 2016 Premiere Dates, Slates JonBenet Ramsey Limited Series|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 21, 2016|accessdate=June 21, 2016| archivedate=October 4, 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161004185632/http://deadline.com/2016/06/cbs-fall-premiere-dates-2016-1201776569/| deadurl=no}}</ref> Following its renewal after the first season, Hayes was fired from the series for unspecified creative reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/cbs-early-renewals-macgyver-superior-donuts-life-in-pieces-hawaii-five-0-blue-bloods-1202049276/|title=CBS Renews 5 Freshman & 11 Returning Series, Including ‘MacGyver’, ‘Superior Donuts’, ‘Life In Pieces’ & ‘Hawaii Five-0’|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/erinn-hayes-leaving-kevin-can-wait-1202453205/|title=Erinn Hayes Leaving CBS’ ‘Kevin Can Wait’|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 3, 2017|accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref> The series would be canceled after one more season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2018/05/12/kevin-can-wait-cancelled-season-3-cbs/|title=Kevin Can Wait Cancelled at CBS After Polarizing Season 2 Shake-Up|first=Ryan|last=Schwartz|date=12 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref>
==Personal life== Hayes attended [[University of Colorado at Boulder]] and graduated in 1998 with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree in performance.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/blogs/college-flashback/2008/09/12/erinn-hayes</ref> Hayes and her high school sweetheart husband,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/kevin-can-wait/cast/215255/|title=Kevin Can Wait Cast: Erinn Hayes|publisher=|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> construction supervisor Jack Hayes, have two daughters named Maggie Mae (born June 10, 2007) and Lilah Grace (born April 29, 2009).<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20250391,00.html Worst Week Star Erinn Hayes is Expecting] People.com, January 6, 2009</ref>
